target_title: GIMP Help - How to upload images

note.body:
You, or your language team manager, needs to have a Gnome Gitlab account, discuss with your language team if they need to review your images first, then:
1. Fork the gimp-help repository.
2. Pull from that fork (not directly from the main gimp-help repository).
3. Add/update the images.
4. Commit the changes with a relevant commit message.
5. Push the changes to your fork.
6. Go to the main gimp-help repository online. At the top it should show you a message that asks you if you want to make a Merge Request (MR). Click that and fill in relevant info; check the box to delete your branch after the MR is accepted.
7. Click the button (can't remember what it says) to create the MR if all is filled in.
8. You then have to wait until I or someone else has time to review and we will either merge if it is ok, or ask you to make changes if we feel that is needed.

note.body:
Curious about somewhat-significant differences in file size, I did some digging. The presets are _defined_ in [src/enc/config_enc.c](https://github.com/webmproject/libwebp/blob/main/src/enc/config_enc.c).

Picture and Photo have a stronger Spatial Noise Shaping filter setting 80) than Default (50), while Drawing has 25 and Icon and Text have 0. I believe this reduces "mosquito noise" from compression artifacts in flat areas. This may blur _intentional_ fine detail, hence less suitable for the last three. Perhaps unsurprisingly, removal of high-frequency content also improves compressibility.

Further context is provided by [src/webp/encode.h](https://github.com/webmproject/libwebp/blob/main/src/webp/encode.h#L95) where we find that filter_strength is 0-100, but filter_sharpness is off at 0, sharpest at 1 and weakest at 7. So photo has greater "sharpness" than picture, which in turn is higher than drawing - but drawing has a lower-_strength_ filter, while picture has the highest strength.

From the table in [src/enc/filter_enc.c](https://github.com/webmproject/libwebp/blob/main/src/enc/filter_enc.c) it seems like this is about defining how fast [filtering to remove rectangular artifacts (deblocking)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deblocking_filter) ramps up. This is why picture compresses best of all mentioned in the above paragraph, at least on some of my test images.

For text, the number of segments is reduced from four to two - perhaps as there's expected to be less variation in macroblocks? Photo has psuedo-random dithering pre-processing as well, perhaps to emulate grain or avoid artifacts.

note.body:
CORRECTION: I now find Help is, in fact, installed on my copy of Gimp 2.10.38. Apparently, that is the version called up by the F1 function key, not the earlier Gimp 2.10.24 version on another partition. (Confusingly, they both appear with the same url.) It would appear Help was packaged with Gimp for Mac in this instance, though maybe not always. On https://www.gimp.org/docs/ it says, "You may have to install the help pages from a separate package (gimp-help)", which probably misled me. 

Maybe a comment on how to check might be included at https://www.gimp.org/docs/ – "Go to Gimp Preferences/Interface/Help System, where you will be told if the user manual is locally installed; a dropdown menu then gives you the option to use either this or online Help, according to preference." That is how I found it, eventually. There is also another dropdown option on Help preferences, which shows blank at first, but gives an option of a User interface language. I suppose that refers to languages other than English, though it is not mentioned in the Help manual. (It seems to have no effect for me.)

Gimp 2.10.38 was also installed on my laptop (running High Sierra as well). It includes a manual which shares the same fault as my desktop version – the Help opens at I.3.2.2. Image Window. (I don't know why.) Such locally-installed manuals are particularly handy when working offline, though they have the same limitation as the online version. Both appear in browser windows, with no Index in a side-bar. I use a work-around, navigating to the Help index first then opening subsequent links in separate tabs. This way, the index is always available. A Home button at the top of the page would be handy for both, as mentioned above. 

Want some more cosmetic recommendations? Here they are anyhow!

• Greater clarity in the Help Index. Main headings – Preface, I. to III., Glossary, Bibliography, A. to F. – could be all caps and bold. Main subheadings e.g. 1. Introduction, could be bold. (I can't see why Keys and Mouse Reference is labelled I. instead of IV.)

• The last item on the page, the 'real' Index, has its own separate page. It starts with Symbols. After that, it is very long and could do with an alphabet string, letters linked to the relevant sections i.e. A-B-C–...etc. that can jump, when clicked, to the entries under A, B, C...etc. 

That's all for now...

note.body:
@Niels In general we don't include the help manual with our GIMP releases, though it may be different on macOS, @lukaso would know that better than me.

In GIMP's preferences you can choose whether to use a locally installed help (if available) or the online help, see Edit -> Preferences -> Help System -> User manual.

GIMP's own help browser was deprecated, IIRC because of difficulties in building and maintaining it's dependencies, so we now use the user's standard browser.

Better navigation within chapters etc is certainly something that would be welcome. Implementing this in the current docbook structure, may need someone that has good knowledge in programming docbook XML.

note.body:
Investigating a bit further, I find the Help I have works well if I open my El Capitan installation (v2.10.24). Then it has a dedicated Gimp window with a sidebar menu (like a browser's bookmarks). It is then easy to navigate to just about anywhere.

My Gimp 2.10.38 does not have the same Gimp window, but accesses the Help from 2.10.24 using Safari. It has no sidebar, and a Gimp menu does not appear in the bookmarks. I'm concluding the .dmg file for my version came without Help included. Gimp's Documents page indicates this could be the case, but suggests there are other files with Help already packaged within the app.

Is there any link for a .dmg fle for 1.10.38 with Help included, or is F1 Help not available within macOS versions? (If there is, with dedicated Help window and sidebar, "breadcrumb links" wouldn't be needed. The extra Home button might be nice, though.)

P.S. I realize the arrows go through the Help menu one item at a time. I was envisaging an instance where one may want to pick out a related page under the same sub-heading, without clicking backwards and forwards page by page.

target_title: Missing description for "Shift Start" in context menu for Paths

note.body: As for why this is there: Sometimes the exact organization of nodes can be important. I agree that this is somewhat obscure, but if you need it (e.g. because you want to make sure a stroking operation starts in a specific point within a closed stroke) it is there.

target_title: Missing description for "Shift Start" in context menu for Paths

note.body:
"Shift Start" makes the current node the new start node of the current stroke by appending the prepending nodes to the end of the stroke. The start node is the one shown with the little pointy corner indicating the stroking direction.

Shifting the start node on open strokes may insert a new segment connecting the previous endpoints, and removes the segment leading into the new start node.

Changes like this are a good change to look for bugs in the GUI, so I had a look. Some small comments here:

1) `images/C/filters/artistic/gimpressionist.png` and `images/C/filters/artistic/gimpressionist1.png` seem to be identical now, so I suppose just one of them could be used in both places in the help.

note.body:
@ajonsson IIUC what is described in #479 is due to using `<term> <phrase>foo</phrase> <phrase>bar</phrase> </term>` (still muddling numerous items into a single `<term>` which I consider a problem) not creating a separate line, while this patch is about `<term>` (no `<phrase>` involved) creating a separate line for itself.

`<term>` is already used correctly (several `<term>` elements following each other with only one UI item included in each element, no use of `<phrase>`) in many GIMP user docs places without issues.
